def nn_model():
    # create model
    model = Sequential()  
    model.add(Dense(1000, activation='relu')) ###Multiple Dense units with Relu activation
    model.add(Dense(500, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))
    return model

In [66]:
# tuned model
def nn_model():
    # create model
    model = Sequential()  
    model.add(Dense(3000, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1500, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dense(1000, activation='relu')) ###Multiple Dense units with Relu activation
    model.add(Dense(500, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))
    return model

CNN model¶

In [88]:
num_classes = 12

model = Sequential([
  layers.Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(img_height, img_width, 3)),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu', bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.L2(0.1)),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Flatten(),
  layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.L2(0.5)),
  layers.Dense(num_classes, activation = 'softmax', bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.L2(0.5))
])

acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']

loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

epochs_range = range(epochs)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
plt.show()

We see that for the CNN the train set accuracy is far ahead of the val_accuracy, and we are in the region of over-fitting here, in spite of the efforts to regularize the later layers of the model, which brought down the train set accuracy from around 95% to the present 91% without significantly affecting the validation(test) set accuracy.

In conclusion, we see that the CNN has the best accuracy amongst all the methods discussed. The training set accuracy is 91.79% and the test set(Validation set) accuracy is 75.24%. This can be because the CNN focuses on the local features of an image, which can lead to a correct classification in short amount of training time even when the input size is very large(7500 variables in this case).
